{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10090,"record_hash":"sha256:952a88599cff3a5e4e3c0f674b322a6b9aa8f0e5409ab61d49e39103817266a8","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Lead with raw ordered records. Add metadata. Do not invent a special summary as the core primitive.\\n\\nFor cross-provider handoff, I’d read in this order:\\n\\n1. Final messages\\n   These tell me what the previous agent claimed was done, what failed, what remains, and what the user was told. Highest signal per token.\\n\\n2. User prompts\\n   These define intent, constraints, later corrections, and priority changes. I need the exact words, not a paraphrase.\\n\\n3. Tool calls and results\\n   Essential for trust. I need to know what files were read, what commands ran, what failed, what changed, what tests passed, and whether a server/session is still running.\\n\\n4. Assistant prose\\n   Useful, but lower trust. It often contains plans, assumptions, and reasoning breadcrumbs. I’d skim it after finals/tool results unless the work is ambiguous.\\n\\nThe proposed tools are close, but I’d tweak the shape.\\n\\n`timeline` should expose enough turn metadata that I can choose what to open without reading everything:\\n\\n- turn key\\n- timestamp\\n- actor sequence\\n- user prompt excerpt\\n- assistant final excerpt\\n- tool call count by type\\n- file paths touched/read if available\\n- command/test summary\\n- status: completed, interrupted, errored, compacted, still-running\\n- token/record counts\\n- provider/model if known\\n\\n`records` should return raw ordered records. Let the agent decide. Summaries are useful as an optional speed layer, but dangerous as the only handoff artifact because they erase the exact failure modes.\\n\\nI would add filters, not a special summary requirement:\\n\\n```text\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --kind user,final,tool_call,tool_result\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --paths crates/foo apps/bar\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --failed\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --commands\\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> --edits\\n```\\n\\nMissing metadata I’d want before safely continuing:\\n\\n- `cwd`, repo root, branch name, commit SHA at turn start/end\\n- dirty worktree summary at turn start/end\\n- files changed by the agent versus pre-existing user changes\\n- exact commands run, exit codes, cwd, env overrides, truncated-output marker\\n- tool result truncation info plus a way to fetch full output\\n- active long-running sessions/processes and ports\\n- whether any write/edit tool succeeded, failed, or partially applied\\n- approval/sandbox/network state\\n- instruction stack used: AGENTS.md paths, skill/plugin instructions, explicit user constraints\\n- timestamps and timezone\\n- model/provider identity, mainly to explain behavioral differences\\n- compaction/resume markers\\n- attachments/images/files referenced\\n- final user-visible response for each completed turn\\n\\nThe core design should be: timeline for navigation, records for truth, metadata for safety. Summaries can be generated on top, but raw ordered records need to stay the source of truth.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}